WEBVTT

00:02.269 --> 00:04.236
[instrumental music]

00:26.060 --> 00:29.061
[instrumental music]

01:01.162 --> 01:02.661
<i> Man 1: You follow</i>
<i> the rules and we're through.</i>

01:02.663 --> 01:04.196
<i> Man 2: Let's go. Come on.</i>
<i> Move back.</i>

01:04.198 --> 01:05.731
<i> Man 3: You're surrounded,</i>
<i> fellows.</i>

01:05.733 --> 01:07.232
[indistinct chatter]

01:07.234 --> 01:08.267
<i> Man 3: When answering</i>
<i> your questions,</i>

01:08.269 --> 01:09.835
<i> we've made a statement and</i>

01:09.837 --> 01:11.437
<i>you should need to be satisfied</i>
<i> with that.</i>

01:11.439 --> 01:13.005
<i> Man 4: We all know</i>
<i> of course that this case</i>

01:13.007 --> 01:14.840
<i> has had a great deal</i>
<i> of publicity.</i>

01:14.842 --> 01:16.475
<i> The lawyers involved</i>
<i> in this case...</i>

01:18.746 --> 01:20.045
<i> Man 5: Not a word!</i>

01:20.047 --> 01:21.280
<i> Man 6: You should bear in mind</i>

01:21.282 --> 01:22.581
<i> that much of what you see</i>

01:22.583 --> 01:24.783
<i> and read is propaganda</i>

01:24.785 --> 01:26.385
<i> from the prosecution.</i>

01:26.387 --> 01:28.187
<i> It's not a fair appraisal</i>

01:28.189 --> 01:29.721
<i> of what in fact occurred.</i>

01:29.723 --> 01:31.990
<i> Man 6: Some of it is</i>
<i> downright false.</i>

01:33.294 --> 01:36.295
[instrumental music]

01:38.065 --> 01:40.899
Benedict: Stay focused.

01:40.901 --> 01:42.468
Stay calm.

01:44.105 --> 01:45.471
Stay honest.

01:47.541 --> 01:49.007
Look them in the eye.

01:51.045 --> 01:52.344
Be polite.

01:53.781 --> 01:55.981
Be respectful.

01:55.983 --> 01:57.950
Listen to the questions.

01:57.952 --> 01:59.451
Think about your answers.

02:01.288 --> 02:04.223
Take your time,
but not too much time.

02:04.225 --> 02:06.758
Give the detail...

02:06.760 --> 02:09.928
not too much detail,
they'll confuse.

02:09.930 --> 02:14.133
Don't stare at the jury,
don't joke with the jury,

02:14.135 --> 02:17.236
don't flirt with the jury.

02:17.238 --> 02:20.172
They're your mother,
they're your father.

02:21.742 --> 02:24.409
They are your fucking future.

02:24.411 --> 02:27.379
[music continues]

02:47.768 --> 02:50.202
[airplane droning]

03:03.951 --> 03:06.919
[tires screeching]

03:15.696 --> 03:17.062
What is happening?

03:19.667 --> 03:20.966
Ellen: What is going on?
Jim: I don't know.

03:23.337 --> 03:25.204
FBI, please vacate the aircraft.

03:25.206 --> 03:26.805
- What is going on, Jim?
Jim: It's...

03:26.807 --> 03:28.540
I'm sure it's some sort of
misunderstanding or--

03:28.542 --> 03:30.809
- Mr. Hoffman, please vacate...
- Why do you know his name?

03:30.811 --> 03:32.144
Benedict: Make no sudden moves.
- Why do they know your name?

03:32.846 --> 03:33.912
Honey.

03:33.914 --> 03:35.214
Vacate the aircraft!

03:35.216 --> 03:37.416
We are vacating
the aircraft, okay.

03:37.418 --> 03:39.551
Let them do their job.

03:39.553 --> 03:41.253
- I don't know.
- It's alright.

03:41.255 --> 03:42.688
Maybe they're confused
or something.

03:42.690 --> 03:44.756
Ellen: Probably just some
accident.

03:44.758 --> 03:49.161
Jim: It's kind of cool.
How old are you guys? Huh?

03:49.163 --> 03:50.762
- Kind of cool, right?
- Babe.

03:50.764 --> 03:53.031
Benedict: Mr. Hoffman,
you're under arrest.

03:53.033 --> 03:54.700
You have the right
to remain silent.

03:54.702 --> 03:56.668
Anything you say
can and will be used against you

03:56.670 --> 03:58.003
in the court of law.

03:58.005 --> 03:59.705
Benedict: Any--
- What are you doing?

03:59.707 --> 04:01.573
Man 3: Anything you say--
- We are on vacation!

04:01.575 --> 04:03.275
These are my children!

04:03.277 --> 04:04.910
- If you need a lawyer--
- We're at Disney Land, asshole!

04:04.912 --> 04:06.445
Oh, fuck it,
just take them away.

04:06.447 --> 04:12.184
What are you doing
with my husband? Jim!

04:12.186 --> 04:14.052
[kids imitating gunshots]

04:14.054 --> 04:15.487
[Ellen sighs]

04:17.191 --> 04:18.890
So, tell me about them?

04:18.892 --> 04:20.259
[sighs]

04:20.261 --> 04:22.194
What can I say?
They were a nice couple.

04:22.196 --> 04:23.729
A nice Christian couple.

04:23.731 --> 04:26.064
This nice Christian couple
we can find no trace of?

04:26.066 --> 04:29.034
Oh, I can be held responsible
for that now, can I?

04:29.036 --> 04:30.535
I'm a pilot, man.

04:30.537 --> 04:33.105
I make a living
transporting shit.

04:33.107 --> 04:34.740
I-- it's all in the manifest.

04:34.742 --> 04:36.208
Sorry, I-- I don't know
what you want from me here.

04:36.210 --> 04:37.476
Here's the thing, Hoffman.

04:37.478 --> 04:39.711
I meet scumbags
like you all the time.

04:39.713 --> 04:42.247
You're the sort of guy
if you could make a 1000 bucks

04:42.249 --> 04:43.949
honest or ten bucks
doing it crooked

04:43.951 --> 04:46.151
you'd do it crooked every time.

04:46.153 --> 04:48.487
I-- I bet you, you'd fuck
your own mother for a quarter.

04:48.489 --> 04:51.623
[laughs] If you're trying
to charm me, sir,

04:51.625 --> 04:52.924
you're not doing a great job--

04:52.926 --> 04:53.959
But worse than fucking
your own mother

04:53.961 --> 04:55.827
you'd fuck your own kids?

04:55.829 --> 04:57.596
You take them on a drug run?

04:57.598 --> 04:59.464
- That is the lowest.
- I took them to Disney World.

04:59.466 --> 05:02.434
- You took them to Bolivia.
- To deliver Bibles.

05:02.436 --> 05:04.770
Okay, I thought
they would have fun.

05:04.772 --> 05:07.105
Except it turns out that Bolivia
is a shithole.

05:07.107 --> 05:08.774
So, we took them to Disney World
on the way back.

05:08.776 --> 05:10.509
You took them
to Bolivia as cover

05:10.511 --> 05:12.010
and you picked up so much coke
you thought

05:12.012 --> 05:14.246
you'd celebrate
in Disney on the way back.

05:14.248 --> 05:15.814
Okay, Ben, listen to me.

05:15.816 --> 05:17.316
Don't call me Ben.

05:17.318 --> 05:19.017
It said, Ben, on your badge.

05:19.019 --> 05:21.820
It says, Benedict J. Tisa,
special agent in charge

05:21.822 --> 05:23.622
Federal Bureau of Investigation.

05:23.624 --> 05:25.023
Special agent in charge?

05:25.793 --> 05:27.626
I like that.

05:27.628 --> 05:29.795
I like you, you know.

05:29.797 --> 05:31.663
And I really like your suit.

05:31.665 --> 05:33.765
You look great, you're the best
dressed guy here.

05:33.767 --> 05:35.000
You know that.

05:35.002 --> 05:37.869
Dressed for the job
you want, right?

05:37.871 --> 05:39.805
Okay, look,
special agent in charge

05:39.807 --> 05:41.273
I swear to you on my life

05:41.275 --> 05:43.241
I knew nothing about
any of this.

05:46.046 --> 05:49.047
[intense music]

05:49.049 --> 05:51.450
Seems like you got a sweet
family out there.

05:54.221 --> 05:56.488
Benedict: But you're not gonna
see them for 30 years.

05:56.490 --> 05:58.256
So, do yourself a favor.

06:02.663 --> 06:04.296
[telephone ringing]

06:06.333 --> 06:08.333
Good lookin' fellow.

06:08.335 --> 06:10.068
I don't know who this other
guy is though.

06:10.070 --> 06:11.970
You know exactly who it is,
because Morgan Hetrick--

06:11.972 --> 06:13.438
Man 8: Sir?

06:18.379 --> 06:19.978
[indistinct chatter]

06:19.980 --> 06:21.980
You landed in Pensacola,
Florida.

06:21.982 --> 06:23.749
You subleased out your plane
and it was

06:23.751 --> 06:26.685
out of your possession
for three nights.

06:26.687 --> 06:28.887
Three magical nights
at Disney World, yes.

06:30.557 --> 06:32.691
Are we done here?

06:32.693 --> 06:35.827
- So, that's it?
- That's it, yeah.

06:35.829 --> 06:37.028
Yeah, I mean I had
the paperwork, you know

06:37.030 --> 06:38.530
you can't argue with paperwork.

06:38.532 --> 06:40.732
Jim, some of those people
that you work with

06:40.734 --> 06:43.034
I do not think
have your best interest in mind.

06:43.036 --> 06:44.770
I agree, no, I-- I think, uh

06:44.772 --> 06:46.371
Bolivia was a pretty
big clue, huh?

06:46.373 --> 06:48.206
- This is a wake up call.
- It's a wake up call.

06:48.208 --> 06:50.609
- We need to start fresh.
- Somewhere new, absolutely.

06:50.611 --> 06:52.377
This time I'm gonna pick where.

06:52.379 --> 06:54.579
- No, no, no, no. No.
- Yeah. We'll put it to a vote.

06:54.581 --> 06:56.047
What do you mean we're gonna
vote? We're not gonna vote.

06:56.049 --> 06:57.416
Yes, we will put it to a vote,

06:57.418 --> 06:59.117
we live in a democracy.

06:59.119 --> 07:01.620
No, no, no, no. No, you think
you live in a democracy.

07:01.622 --> 07:04.456
All in favor of mom choosing
where we live next.

07:04.458 --> 07:06.625
Jim: Oh, hey, guys,
come on, think about it.

07:06.627 --> 07:07.959
We're gonna end up
livin' in some dump.

07:07.961 --> 07:10.061
You know, your mom has no taste.

07:10.063 --> 07:11.563
She married you.

07:11.565 --> 07:12.798
[laughing]

07:13.967 --> 07:15.600
[instrumental music]

07:45.666 --> 07:47.666
[music continues]

07:47.668 --> 07:49.100
Yeah?

07:49.102 --> 07:51.102
It's a really nice neighborhood,
honey.

07:51.104 --> 07:54.072
Yeah, don't worry,
it'll be fine.

07:54.074 --> 07:55.674
Only the best for my family.

07:55.676 --> 07:58.243
Go ahead, door's open.
Go in, check it out.

07:58.245 --> 08:00.278
Howard: Mr. Hoffman.

08:00.280 --> 08:03.048
Who are you exactly?

08:04.351 --> 08:05.584
- Well, I'm not really--
- No, no, no.

08:05.586 --> 08:07.419
Don't answer that,
Mr. Hoffman.

08:07.421 --> 08:09.955
It was a rhetorical question.

08:09.957 --> 08:11.823
So, we're to find out
exactly who you are,

08:11.825 --> 08:13.792
we're gonna find out
what wasn't quite forthcoming

08:13.794 --> 08:16.495
with the prosecution evidence.

08:16.497 --> 08:20.031
Pauma valley,
it's beautiful up there.

08:20.033 --> 08:21.333
Not cheap though, is it?

08:23.303 --> 08:24.836
Sorry, do you want me
to answer that one?

08:24.838 --> 08:27.372
[crowd laughing]

08:27.374 --> 08:29.641
- Yes.
- No, sir, not cheap.

08:29.643 --> 08:32.644
- You have a mortgage? Renting?
- Renting.

08:32.646 --> 08:34.980
- And what's the rent like?
- Sixteen hundred a month.

08:34.982 --> 08:37.816
[whistles] That's, uh,
that's a lot of money.

08:37.818 --> 08:40.619
Why don't we take a quick look
at your, your IRS returns,

08:40.621 --> 08:42.354
see how you can, uh,
afford such, uh,

08:42.356 --> 08:44.055
a nice spread in Pauma valley.

08:44.057 --> 08:46.291
What would you say, at random,

08:46.293 --> 08:48.660
you filed for in 1980?

08:48.662 --> 08:50.128
I did not file in 1980.

08:50.130 --> 08:51.563
Did you file in 1979?

08:51.565 --> 08:53.131
- No, sir, I did not.
- 1978?

08:53.133 --> 08:54.466
- No, sir.
- '77?

08:54.468 --> 08:55.534
1977?

08:55.536 --> 08:57.369
[crowd laughing]

08:59.006 --> 09:01.406
You think this is funny,
Mr. Hoffman?

09:01.408 --> 09:02.807
[chuckles] No, sir.

09:02.809 --> 09:05.310
You do realize
that it is illegal

09:05.312 --> 09:06.845
not to file a tax return?

09:06.847 --> 09:08.213
Yes, sir.

09:08.215 --> 09:11.683
But you did file in 1982.

09:11.685 --> 09:13.084
How come?

09:13.086 --> 09:14.920
Just tryin'
to do the right thing.

09:14.922 --> 09:17.255
Well, there is a first time
for everything.

09:17.257 --> 09:19.257
[laughter]

09:20.193 --> 09:22.327
[humming]

09:22.329 --> 09:24.563
Boy 1: You're in prison.
Boy 2: Yeah, try to escape.

09:24.565 --> 09:26.765
Boy 3: Try to escape.
Try to escape.

09:26.767 --> 09:29.501
Yeah, just keep distracting her.

09:29.503 --> 09:31.102
Hey! Guys, what's going on here?

09:31.104 --> 09:34.039
Dad, dad, o-- okay
if we go play in their pool?

09:34.041 --> 09:35.440
- Please.
- Please let us play.

09:35.442 --> 09:36.575
Hold on, buddy,
I mean, these guys

09:36.577 --> 09:37.776
look like trouble if you ask me.

09:37.778 --> 09:39.110
- Mom?
- It's time to go home.

09:39.112 --> 09:40.579
- Mommy.
- Hi, my love.

09:40.581 --> 09:42.080
Cristina: Good, good, good.

09:42.082 --> 09:44.249
Hi, I hope they're not being
a nuisance.

09:44.251 --> 09:46.351
No, not at all, no.
More than welcome.

09:46.353 --> 09:49.087
Oh, we haven't had a chance to
welcome you to the neighborhood.

09:49.089 --> 09:52.457
We're always coming and going.
Cristina.

09:52.459 --> 09:55.226
Oh, I'm... Sorry. Uh, hey.
Hi, Jim.

09:55.228 --> 09:56.728
Hi.

09:56.730 --> 09:58.463
Mom, can they come swim with us?

09:58.465 --> 10:00.865
It's alright with me if that's
alright with their dad.

10:00.867 --> 10:02.567
Yeah, no, of course.
They're very good.

10:02.569 --> 10:04.402
- Thank you so much.
- Yeah, no problem.

10:04.404 --> 10:06.571
- Ni-- nice to meet you.
- Let's go! Come on.

10:06.573 --> 10:08.039
Come on, baby.

10:08.041 --> 10:09.441
Mommy. Are we going?

10:09.443 --> 10:11.776
Am I gonna try on
my new bathing suit now?

10:11.778 --> 10:12.978
Aye-aye-yay!

10:20.587 --> 10:22.854
[instrumental music]

10:35.335 --> 10:37.335
[engine cranking]

10:38.672 --> 10:40.372
Come on.

10:43.944 --> 10:46.411
- Damn it.
John: That's a nice looking car.

10:47.914 --> 10:50.148
O-- oh! Yeah, thanks.

10:50.150 --> 10:53.184
John: 389 cubic inch V-8 engine.

10:53.186 --> 10:58.023
Three double barrel carburetors,
speed, performance, handling.

10:59.626 --> 11:01.292
Back in the day...

11:01.294 --> 11:03.561
the girls loved it.

11:06.299 --> 11:07.766
Would you mind if I, uh...

11:09.503 --> 11:11.503
Yeah, be my guest.

11:15.942 --> 11:18.343
Yeah, there she is.

11:18.345 --> 11:19.644
Alright.

11:19.646 --> 11:21.346
Turn it over.

11:21.348 --> 11:22.681
Okay.

11:22.683 --> 11:24.683
[engine cranking]

11:26.687 --> 11:27.919
[laughs]

11:31.124 --> 11:32.457
How the hell did you do that?

11:32.459 --> 11:34.426
Ah, beginner's luck.

11:36.129 --> 11:38.563
And I designed it.

11:38.565 --> 11:41.966
You designed it?
What, what, you designed what?

11:43.303 --> 11:45.704
What, you designed the GTO?

11:48.475 --> 11:50.575
Holy shit. Holy shit.

11:50.577 --> 11:52.377
You're John DeLorean,
aren't you?

11:52.379 --> 11:54.245
[laughs]

11:54.247 --> 11:58.216
Amazing. Well, that, I... Hey,
great job on this, you know.

11:58.218 --> 11:59.484
I mean, Shakespeare writes
a play, he at least

11:59.486 --> 12:00.652
gets to put his name on it.

12:00.654 --> 12:02.554
Well, I might do that yet.

12:02.556 --> 12:06.357
Yeah. Uh... Hey, hold on
a second, okay? Will you?

12:06.359 --> 12:08.326
I'll be right back.
Don't go anywhere.

12:10.397 --> 12:12.931
Jim: Where are the beers?
Ellen: In the fridge!

12:12.933 --> 12:14.933
Jim: No, I'm in the fridge here.

12:14.935 --> 12:16.234
Wait, wait, wait, wait.
I got 'em. I got 'em.

12:16.236 --> 12:17.802
Thank you.

12:20.173 --> 12:23.942
- You a pilot?
- Um... Here you go.

12:23.944 --> 12:25.677
- I-- I used to be.
- Good.

12:25.679 --> 12:26.911
You know, it's been a long time

12:26.913 --> 12:29.347
since I got my hands dirty.

12:29.349 --> 12:30.949
Well, I mean, you know,
if it's in the blood

12:30.951 --> 12:33.685
it's in the blood.

12:33.687 --> 12:36.054
Ha, John DeLorean!

12:36.056 --> 12:39.557
In my house?
It's something else.

12:39.559 --> 12:41.593
Uh, so, I mean, what are you...
What are you doing now?

12:41.595 --> 12:43.962
You-- you still over
at the GM, yeah?

12:43.964 --> 12:46.698
No, I got out of that racket.

12:46.700 --> 12:49.234
Now, I'm working on something
for myself.

12:49.236 --> 12:52.403
Um. Nice. Nice. Good for you.

12:52.405 --> 12:54.606
What, um, may I ask, um...

12:54.608 --> 12:57.008
She still doesn't sound right.

13:00.313 --> 13:01.780
So what, they,
they won't let you

13:01.782 --> 13:03.615
do your own thing
over a Pontiac?

13:03.617 --> 13:05.984
Oh, Christ, no. General Motors.

13:05.986 --> 13:08.119
Ford. Chrysler.

13:08.121 --> 13:10.155
There's hasn't been a single
honest to God innovation

13:10.157 --> 13:12.590
in 20 years,
all they do is tinker.

13:12.592 --> 13:13.992
They'll, uh,

13:13.994 --> 13:16.227
smooth a corner
or automate a wiper

13:16.229 --> 13:18.496
and hype it as
some great new model.

13:18.498 --> 13:20.765
Oh! Oh-oh.
Better get that.

13:20.767 --> 13:23.735
- But it's all just bullshit.
- Oh, where are you?

13:23.737 --> 13:26.070
Oh, here it is.

13:26.072 --> 13:28.439
Ah! Shit! Shh!

13:28.441 --> 13:29.808
- You alright?
- Yeah.

13:29.810 --> 13:32.944
I cut myself.
Fucking rust bucket.

13:32.946 --> 13:35.013
Take this.

13:35.015 --> 13:36.514
Oh. Thanks.

13:36.516 --> 13:38.149
I think you'll live.

13:39.986 --> 13:41.619
John: Rust.

13:41.621 --> 13:43.354
Every car in America is dying

13:43.356 --> 13:46.157
the minute
it leaves the factory.

13:46.159 --> 13:48.660
But my car...

13:48.662 --> 13:50.929
now my car is...

13:52.966 --> 13:58.002
My car will be made of
brushed stainless steel.

13:58.004 --> 13:59.871
Rear mounted engine.

13:59.873 --> 14:02.507
The underbody will be
made of two large molded parts.

14:02.509 --> 14:04.843
uh, the frame and the body are
one and it's made of

14:04.845 --> 14:07.846
of stainless steel, you see,
so, it'll last forever.

14:07.848 --> 14:09.347
It'll be safest car on the road.

14:09.349 --> 14:10.982
- Mm.
- And, um, and airbags, Jim.

14:10.984 --> 14:13.151
- Do you know about airbags?
- Uh, no.

14:13.153 --> 14:15.620
I want this car
under 2200 pounds.

14:15.622 --> 14:17.021
0 to 60 in 8 seconds.

14:17.023 --> 14:18.323
20 miles per gallon
in the city,

14:18.325 --> 14:20.191
30 miles per gallon
on the highway.

14:20.193 --> 14:23.728
I want a suspension system
that is designed by a computer.

14:24.831 --> 14:26.030
And the doors, Jim...

14:27.033 --> 14:28.867
The doors... Heh.

14:30.503 --> 14:33.538
- They're gull-winged.
- Oh, yeah.

14:33.540 --> 14:35.340
- Right?
- Look at this, they're some...

14:35.342 --> 14:37.408
Oh, sorry, um...

14:37.410 --> 14:39.177
Yeah, it's like science fiction
or something.

14:39.179 --> 14:40.812
It's the future.

14:40.814 --> 14:42.480
- They lift straight up.
- Oh.

14:42.482 --> 14:45.216
Right? You can park it
almost anywhere.

14:45.218 --> 14:47.318
It's more expensive 'cause
you've got to counter balance it

14:47.320 --> 14:48.887
against gravity,
but it's worth it.

14:48.889 --> 14:50.688
Sure, sure, so, you just
kinda come up with, like, uh

14:50.690 --> 14:53.424
an affordable
anti-gravity device.

14:53.426 --> 14:54.626
And, uh...

