actually lives on our block.

16:42.135 --> 16:43.668
- All sounds pretty idyllic.
- Yeah?

16:43.670 --> 16:45.436
Yeah. No, it is.
It's pretty idyllic.

16:45.438 --> 16:47.638
Do you think something's missing
missing from this equation now?

16:47.640 --> 16:50.141
Something a little...
imbalanced?

16:50.143 --> 16:52.276
Yeah, I don't know.
Maybe. I...

16:52.278 --> 16:53.878
Maybe? Listen.

16:53.880 --> 16:56.280
We're not in the business
of arresting

16:56.282 --> 16:58.483
every street corner dealer
that catches your eye.

16:58.485 --> 17:00.218
We've got bigger fish to fry.

17:00.220 --> 17:01.953
Uh, no. No, no, no. Hey, look.

17:01.955 --> 17:04.222
I told ya, I can't go there,
okay? The guy'll kill me.

17:04.224 --> 17:06.457
Well, there's two versions
of the Morgan Hetrick story.

17:06.459 --> 17:08.126
Version one, he's your pal,

17:08.128 --> 17:09.660
and yet he sent you to Bolivia

17:09.662 --> 17:12.330
and he hid a shitload of coke
in your plane.

17:12.332 --> 17:13.965
Or you're in cahoots.

17:16.836 --> 17:18.803
Your buddy organizes more
flights than Pan-Am.

17:18.805 --> 17:21.272
He flies in half the coke
that comes into California.

17:22.709 --> 17:24.709
Your buddy, Morgan Hetrick,
has millions

17:24.711 --> 17:26.844
sitting in the Cayman Islands
he can't access

17:26.846 --> 17:28.212
and we'd like to get
our hands on it.

17:28.214 --> 17:29.914
So, you have a choice.

17:31.017 --> 17:32.750
You work with us on this,

17:32.752 --> 17:35.119
we bring him in, you go free.

17:36.022 --> 17:37.655
You say no,

17:37.657 --> 17:39.857
we fuck you out
of your nice house,

17:39.859 --> 17:41.359
you go to prison,

17:41.361 --> 17:43.094
your wife goes to prison

17:43.096 --> 17:44.862
as an accessory

17:44.864 --> 17:47.265
and your kids go in
to the system.

17:47.267 --> 17:49.367
[dramatic music]

17:49.369 --> 17:51.436
Actually, you don't have
a choice.

18:05.718 --> 18:08.453
¶ I'm lucky so lucky ¶

18:08.455 --> 18:09.720
Jim: Boy, look at this place.

18:09.722 --> 18:10.855
How is this house across

18:10.857 --> 18:11.856
the street from our house?

18:11.858 --> 18:13.858
Hi...

18:13.860 --> 18:16.027
- Well, not bad.
- Jim.

18:16.029 --> 18:17.628
- Hi.
- How are you doing?

18:17.630 --> 18:19.030
- Good. How are you?
- Oh.

18:19.032 --> 18:20.398
- Great.
- Heh-heh.

18:20.400 --> 18:22.400
Hi, I'm Cristina,
I'm John's wife.

18:22.402 --> 18:23.901
- Ellen.
- So great to meet you.

18:23.903 --> 18:25.570
You look so lovely.

18:25.572 --> 18:27.138
Well, let me introduce you.

18:27.140 --> 18:28.940
- Come on.
- Okay. Um...

18:30.210 --> 18:32.944
- Ladies, this is Ellen.
- Hi.

18:32.946 --> 18:34.946
Ellen's Jim
is in the airline business.

18:34.948 --> 18:36.314
- Oh, neat.
- Yes.

18:36.316 --> 18:37.915
We just moved in
across the street.

18:37.917 --> 18:39.550
- Oh.
- Oh, lovely.

18:39.552 --> 18:41.752
- Hi. Uh, can I get a drink?
Man 7: Yes, sir.

18:41.754 --> 18:44.822
Um, whiskey on the rocks,
please.

18:44.824 --> 18:47.391
[indistinct chatter]

18:47.393 --> 18:48.826
Bill: Ladies and gentlemen!

18:48.828 --> 18:51.062
Come out of the bar!

18:51.064 --> 18:53.464
Come out of the half rooms.
Gather around.

18:53.466 --> 18:55.933
Ladies and gentlemen,
I would like to introduce you

18:55.935 --> 18:58.636
to a man who needs
no introduction.

18:58.638 --> 19:02.006
The most successful
auto executive in living memory.

19:02.008 --> 19:05.243
The youngest ever, head of
a division at General Motors

19:05.245 --> 19:07.612
and now founder
of the DeLorean Motor Company,

19:07.614 --> 19:10.248
I give you Mr. John DeLorean.

19:10.250 --> 19:12.316
- Thank you.
- Glad to meet you.

19:12.318 --> 19:13.651
It's good to see you here.

19:13.653 --> 19:15.253
Oh, hey, thank you so much.

19:15.255 --> 19:17.255
Well, thank you, Bill.

19:17.257 --> 19:19.323
Thank you, all. Um...

19:19.325 --> 19:21.492
Boy, it's lovely
to see you all here,

19:21.494 --> 19:24.462
um, but you know there's no
such thing as a free beer...

19:24.464 --> 19:26.130
[laughter]

19:26.132 --> 19:27.498
So you'll have to listen to me

19:27.500 --> 19:29.100
bang the drum for our new car.

19:29.102 --> 19:30.501
[laughter]

19:30.503 --> 19:33.137
I know some of you
haven't signed up yet,

19:33.139 --> 19:35.106
and I wanted to show you
something I received

19:35.108 --> 19:36.774
in the mail today.

19:36.776 --> 19:38.676
- It's a check...
- Ooh.

19:38.678 --> 19:42.113
From a new investor
for $600,000.

19:42.115 --> 19:43.848
- Wow.
- Yeah.

19:43.850 --> 19:46.817
And, uh, what's the name
on that check?

19:46.819 --> 19:48.452
It's a Mr. Johnny Carson.

19:48.454 --> 19:50.421
[cheering]

19:52.825 --> 19:55.393
And that's all well and good,
but I...

19:55.395 --> 19:58.129
You know I wanted
to get serious for a minute.

19:58.131 --> 20:00.298
In the America I grew up in,

20:00.300 --> 20:03.868
a man was defined
by the work he did.

20:03.870 --> 20:06.804
But there was precious
little work to be had.

20:06.806 --> 20:08.339
Very few opportunities.

20:08.341 --> 20:10.174
[instrumental music]

20:10.176 --> 20:12.910
But that didn't stop me
from dreaming.

20:14.714 --> 20:16.414
My father,

20:16.416 --> 20:18.316
oh, he knew hard times.

20:18.318 --> 20:20.585
But he was a smart man.

20:20.587 --> 20:22.653
He said, "It's okay to dream

20:22.655 --> 20:25.156
as long as you combine
those dreams

20:25.158 --> 20:27.325
with hard work."

20:27.327 --> 20:29.493
When I was 14,

20:29.495 --> 20:31.662
he bought this battered down,
old Chevy

20:31.664 --> 20:34.198
and took it apart
into 500 pieces

20:34.200 --> 20:36.200
on our front lawn.

20:36.202 --> 20:38.669
He said, "Son,

20:38.671 --> 20:41.772
if you can put that car
back together, then it's yours."

20:43.209 --> 20:46.210
And that's exactly what I did.

20:46.212 --> 20:48.346
Three days and nights
it took me.

20:48.348 --> 20:51.515
I didn't eat or sleep,
but I did it.

20:52.619 --> 20:55.219
And when it was done...

20:55.221 --> 20:58.389
that car drove like a dream.

20:58.391 --> 21:01.425
And that is my intention
with the DeLorean motorcar,

21:01.427 --> 21:04.295
to build a dream car,

21:04.297 --> 21:08.799
something the great American
public can aspire to owning.

21:08.801 --> 21:12.203
Ladies and gentlemen, it is my
great pleasure to present to you

21:12.205 --> 21:15.439
the latest design
for the DeLorean motor car.

21:15.441 --> 21:16.774
Uh, Roy, Bill.

21:16.776 --> 21:19.143
[dramatic music]

21:19.145 --> 21:20.544
[crowd gasping]

21:20.546 --> 21:22.513
[cheering]

21:24.050 --> 21:25.316
[all gasping]

21:25.318 --> 21:27.952
[cheering]

21:27.954 --> 21:29.754
We're going to design a car,

21:29.756 --> 21:31.489
we're going to build a factory,

21:31.491 --> 21:34.625
we are going
to create 2000 jobs,

21:34.627 --> 21:37.728
we are going to produce
30,000 cars a year

21:37.730 --> 21:41.565
and we are going to do it all
in 18 months.

21:41.567 --> 21:43.801
If you haven't signed up yet,

21:43.803 --> 21:46.671
what are you waiting for?

21:46.673 --> 21:49.473
[cheering]

21:49.475 --> 21:50.808
- Nice job.
- Roy.

21:50.810 --> 21:54.078
You know that's so amazing...

21:54.080 --> 21:55.713
Everybody... [chuckles]

21:58.818 --> 22:00.184
You really think
he can pull this off?

22:00.186 --> 22:02.586
- Oh, I know he can.
- Yeah?

22:02.588 --> 22:03.688
How long you been working
with him?

22:03.690 --> 22:05.156
Since the very beginning.

22:05.158 --> 22:06.457
John: Hey, good to see you.
Good to see you.

22:06.459 --> 22:07.692
I want you take a look
at that car.

22:07.694 --> 22:10.461
It's a good looking car.
Thank you.

